# Resistant poplars in the field: Assigning -5 to NA to avoid confusion in R

dist

  • Field resistance
    Seems that the poplars are in intermediate resistance, on average. For a note, field resistance is measured using scoring system from 1 - 6; score 1 means that infection covers only a small area of leaves, score 6 means that infection covers almost all area of poplar leaves. In other words, when field resistance score is 1 then the poplar is resistant, when field resistance score is 6 then the poplar is susceptible.

    In the field, the score is a little bit more than 3, which means that the infection moderately covers poplars leaf area. This being said that the poplars are either resistant or susceptible in the field.

  • Lab resistance, parameter: latent period
    On average, poplars started showing the first infection (or symptoms) on day 8.5 after inoculation. Day 8.5 means that the infection starts on day 8 after midday. Seems that the poplars can inhibit the colonization of the pathogen until day 8, on average.

  • Lab resistance, parameter: number of spores
    Poplar individuals show a variable number of spores. Because of this, there are not many individuals that have similar number of spores (see the Y-axis scale). It seems that there are 2 peaks in the distribution, showing the segregation between indivdiuals. This is the indication that the population is made of 2 groups of populations. On average, the poplars are colonized by 30 spores (max = 56 spores) even though there are not so many poplars colonized by 30 spores. There are more poplars colonized by either 25 or 36 spores, indicating that the poplars may be moderately resistant.

  • Lab resistance, parameter: size of spores
    On average, the size of spores is scored closer to 4 than to 3. It shows that the poplars cannot inhibit the development of the pathogens spore once the spores colonize the poplars. It shows that the poplars are rather susceptible for this type of pathogen (code: rust 93JE3)

  • Overall
    The poplars are closer to being susceptible than to being resistant in the lab for this particular type of pathogen (code: rust 93JE3). Despite being able to inhibit the colonization of pathogens spores on the leaves, the poplars couldnt inhibit the growth of pathogens spores at the end. While it is good to inhibit the number of spore colonization, it is more important to inhibit the growth of spore so that the spore do not cover the leaves. This is because if the poplars allow the spore to cover the leaf area, the poplars are at risk to reduced growth due to inefficient photosynthesize.

Obj 3 Observing the origins of poplar individuals collected from parent population and natural population

x_labs = c("Natural Population", "Parent Population")

ggplot(wild_yr2000_new, aes(x = Classe)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = Classe)) + 
  geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = ..count..), vjust = -0.5) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = x_labs) +
  ggpubr::fill_palette("jco") +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "Counts", title = "The types of black poplar individuals") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        legend.position = "none")

The poplar individuals were consisted of poplars collected from natural population and from parent population.

Parent population means that these poplars have been used in a breeding program. Poplars are managed as hybrids. Hybrids are individuals created from 2 different species. In this case, hybrid poplar can be created from parents Populus deltoides x Populus nigra (P. nigra is the scientific name of black poplar). So poplar individuals collected from parent population means that these individuals are used as a parent in breeding hybrid poplars.

So lets see their origins.

Obj 3.1 The origins of poplar from natural and parent population

# Insert a new column for "Region"
library(tibble)
wild_copy = wild_yr2000_new

wild_copy = tibble::add_column(wild_copy, "Region" = "NA", .after = "Population")

# Assigning the population to their region
for (j in c(1:nrow(wild_copy))) {
  if(wild_copy$Population[j] == "ValdeLoire" | 
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "Selles_sur_Cher" |
    wild_copy$Population[j] == "Bonny"){
    wild_copy$Region[j] = "Centre_Val_de_Loire"
  } 
  
  if(wild_copy$Population[j] == "Ramires" | 
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "ValAllier" |
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "St_Jean_de_Maurienne" |
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "Meximieux" | 
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "St_Genix_sur_Guiers"){
    wild_copy$Region[j] = "Auvergne_Rhone_Alpes"
  } 
  
  if(wild_copy$Population[j] == "Tarbes" | 
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "Nohdes" |
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "Sauveterre" |
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "Cauterets"){
    wild_copy$Region[j] = "Occitanie"
  }
  
  if(wild_copy$Population[j] == "StPriv" | 
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "La_Celle_sur_Loire"){
    wild_copy$Region[j] = "Bourgogne_Franche_Comte"
  }
  
  if(wild_copy$Population[j] == "Sarrazin" | 
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "Gave-Mauleon" |
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "Baudreix" |
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "Baliros" | 
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "Assat"){
    wild_copy$Region[j] = "Nouvelle_Aquitaine"
  }
  
  if(wild_copy$Population[j] == "Pont_de_C" | 
     wild_copy$Population[j] == "Cunault"){
    wild_copy$Region[j] = "Pays_de_la_Loire"
  }
  
  if(wild_copy$Population[j] == "Cazebonne"){
    wild_copy$Region[j] = "Bordeaux"
  }
  
}

Obj 3.2 Comparison of resistance between poplars from natural population and from parent population

In this section, I would like to show you the resistance between the two populations. Are poplars from natural population resisting better to leaf rust than the poplars from parent population?

Field resistance and spore size

# Summary statistics with aggregate function

# Length
aggregate = aggregate(wild_yr2000_new$Classe, by = list(Classe = wild_yr2000_new$Classe), 
                       FUN = length)
names(aggregate)[2] = "length"

# Function mean
mean.fun = function(x){
  aggregate(x,
            by = list(Classe = wild_yr2000_new$Classe),
            FUN = mean)
}

# Function sd 
sd.fun = function(x){
  aggregate(x,
            by = list(Classe = wild_yr2000_new$Classe),
            FUN = sd)
}

# Plotting the comparison
compare_NM = ggplot(wild_yr2000_new, aes(x = Classe, y = Notemax.2010)) +

compare

In terms of field resistance:
The poplars from natural populations show lower field resistance than parent population.

In terms of spore size in the lab:
The poplars from natural populations have lower spore size than the parents (on average). This shows the ability of the poplars from natural populations to better prevent the development of pathogens spores on their leaves, in laboratory setting. It also means that in the lab, P. nigra itself is able to prevent the development of the spore, rather than when it is paired with other Populus species in a breeding program.

Latent period

# Latent period
compare_LP = ggplot(wild_yr2000_new, aes(x = Classe, y = latence.93JE3.2010)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill = Classe)) +
  ggpubr::fill_palette("jco") +
  stat_summary(fun = "mean", geom = "point", size = 3, color = "red", shape = 15) +
  geom_jitter(color = "grey", width = .1) +

       x = "Class",
       y = "Days") +
  scale_x_discrete(limit = c("nigrapop", "parent 14x13"),
                   labels = c("Natural Population", "Parent Population")) +
  ylim(7, 12) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

compare_LP

In terms of latent period in the lab: The poplars from natural populations start showing symptoms in a much later day than the poplars from the parent population. It shows the ability of the poplars from natural populations to prevent the accumulation of pathogen on the leaves.

When the poplars are able to prevent the accumulation of the pathogen, they are more likely to prevent the growth of the pathogen on the leaves. Thus when they start showing symptoms in a much later day, they tend to have fewer spores with smaller size on the leaves than the other poplars that show symptoms in an earlier day.

Spore number

# Number of spores

compare_NS

In terms of number of spores: The poplars from natural populations have fewer number of spores than the parent. It relates to the inhibiting actions of latent period, and it also leads to the smaller spore size.

Bottom line

So the bottom line is, poplars from natural population show lower resistance in the field than the poplars from parent population. However, in the laboratory setting (a controlled environment), the poplars from natural population show better resistance than those from parent population, in a way that they are able to inhibit the growth of the pathogen.

Obj 4 Correlation between field resistance and lab resistance

To observe the relationships between the parameters of resistance. Furthermore, to see if field resistance can be explained by the parameters of lab resistance or not.

corr

It seems that there are no clear correlation between field and lab resistance. It seems unclear whether lab resistance can explain or predict field resistance.

Obj 5 Correlation between parameters of lab resistance

In this section, I want to evaluate the correlation between the components of lab resistance. I will just evaluate the correlation between two components: latent period (LP) and spore size (SS).

# Designing the main correlation plot latence x taille
main_cor = ggplot(data = wild_yr2000_new, aes(x = latence.93JE3.2010,
                                              y = taille.93JE3.2010,
                                              color = Classe)) +
  labs(x = "Latent Period (days)", y = "Spore size (score)") +
  geom_point(aes(color = Classe)) +
  ggpubr::color_palette("jco") +
  stat_cor(method = "pearson", cor.coef.name = "R",
           digits = 2, label.x.npc = "center") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

# Because I differentiated correlation for parent and nigrapop, I want to provide
# the density histogram for poplars from parent and nigrapop

# Density histogram for latent period, plotted at x axis
xdens = axis_canvas(main_cor, axis = "x") +  # create the canvas base
  geom_density(data = wild_yr2000_new, 
               aes(x = latence.93JE3.2010, fill = Classe),
               alpha = 0.7, size = 0.2) +  # density histogram for latence
  ggpubr::fill_palette("jco")  # color palette for fill 

# Density histogram for taille, plotted at y axis
ydens = axis_canvas(main_cor, axis = "y", coord_flip = TRUE) +
  geom_density(data = wild_yr2000_new, 
               aes(x = taille.93JE3.2010, fill = Classe),
               alpha = 0.7, size = 0.2) +  # density histogram for taille
  coord_flip() +  # flipping the coordinate, 90 degrees
  ggpubr::fill_palette("jco")

# Adding xdens on the x axis of correlation plot
main_cor1 = cowplot::insert_xaxis_grob(main_cor, xdens,
                                       grid::unit(0.2, "null"), 
                                       position = "top")

# Adding ydens on the y axis of correlation plot
main_cor2 = cowplot::insert_yaxis_grob(main_cor1, ydens,
                                       grid::unit(0.2, "null"), 
                                       position = "right")

cowplot::ggdraw(main_cor2)

# Saving the plot
ggsave("correlation_plot.png",
       device = "png",
       width = 15,
       height = 10,
       units = "cm",
       dpi = 300)

It seems that there is a clear correlation between the parameters of lab resistance (latent period and spore size).
